==English==

===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg}}

# A place to buy items.
#: ''I need to get some milk from the grocery '''store'''.''
# {{archaic}} A place to store items.
#: ''This building used to be a '''store''' for old tires.''
# A supply held in storage.
#: ''We have a large '''store''' of beer, in case we're snowed in.''
# {{computing}} {{archaic}} Memory.
#: ''The main '''store''' of 1000 36-bit words seemed large at the time.''

====Translations====
*Chinese: [[商店]] (1)
*German: [[Laden]] {{m}} (1), [[Lager]] {{n}} (2), [[Vorrat]] {{m}} (3), [[Speicher]] {{m}} (4)
*Swedish: [[lager]] {{n}} (2,3)
*Ukrainian: [[крамниця]] (kramn'''y'''c'a) {{f}} (1), [[комора]] (kom'''o'''ra) {{f}} (2), [[запас]] (zap'''a'''s) {{m}} (3), [[пам'ять]] (p'''a'''mjat') {{f}} (4)

===Transitive verb===
{{en-infl-reg-other-e|stor|e}}

# To keep while not in use, generally in a place meant for that purpose.
#: ''I'll store these books in the attic.''
# {{computing}} Write into memory or registers.
#: ''This operation stores the result on the stack.''

====Translations====
*German: [[lagern]] (1), [[speichern]] (2)
*Swedish: [[lagra]] (1,2), [[spara]] (2)

===Intransitive verb===
{{en-infl-reg-other-e|stor|e}}

# To stay in good condition while stored.
#: ''I don't think that kind of cheese will store well at room temperature.''

====Translations====
*German: [[sich]] [[halten]]
*Swedish: [[hålla sig]]

===Synonyms===
*(''a place to buy items'') [[shop]]

